<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,317,1075,1101]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[332,557,1076,1101]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="falciferella">
<emphasis box="[332,557,1076,1101]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Perittia falciferella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a medium-sized and broad-winged species with the forewing mottled by the greyish-brown tips of its scales. In female genitalia, the peculiarly shaped signum separates this species well from all the other known 
<taxonomicName box="[507,650,1153,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Elachistinae">Elachistinae</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,288,1191,1217]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[303,391,1192,1218]" captionStart="FIGURES 32 – 36" captionStartId="14.[151,273,1598,1622]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,197,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,197,1575]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 32 – 36. Adults of Perittia species. 32, P. gnoma sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: 000005176; 33, P. falciferella sp. n., female, paratype. Specimen ID: 000005180; 34, P. spatulata sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: 000005159; 35, P. spatulata sp. n., female, paratype. Specimen ID: 000005172; 36, P. tantilla sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5148. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189258/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[358,391,1192,1218]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="33.0">33</number>
</figureCitation>
). Forewing length 3.3–3.7 mm; wingspan 7.3–8.1 mm (n= 
<number box="[1077,1091,1192,1218]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="3.0">3</number>
). Head: Frons whitish; vertex and neck tuft greyish brown, mottled due to white transversal streak before dark tips of scales; labial palpus very short and straight, greyish brown; scape broader than flagellum, greyish brown with white transversal streak before dark scale tips; flagellum greyish brown annulated with paler rings, in distal half with slightly raised scales. Thorax, tegula and forewing greyish brown, mottled with greyish-brown tips of scales; slightly raised blackish-brown scales forming two small spots on forewing: one at 
<number box="[1022,1033,1385,1411]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1045,1060,1385,1411]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="3.0">3</number>
and another, smaller one at 
<number box="[1390,1404,1385,1411]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[1415,1430,1385,1411]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="5.0">5</number>
; fringe brownish grey, mottled due to white transversal streak before dark tips of some scales. Hindwing including fringe brownish grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" box="[197,398,1501,1527]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,260,1501,1527]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,404,1539,1565]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[421,566,1540,1566]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 43" captionStartId="17.[151,270,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[172,1436,482,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,465,1933]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 43. Perittia falciferella sp. n., female genitalia, holotype. 41, general view. Scale bar 0.2 mm; 42, caudal part of ductus bursae; 43, signum. Gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 477, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5178." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189260/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Figs. 
<number box="[488,566,1540,1566]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="42.0" valueMax="43.0" valueMin="41.0">41–43</number>
</figureCitation>
). Papillae anales short, with scattered long setae; posteriorly with zone of very short fine setae mixed with longer ones. Tergite 
<number box="[803,818,1578,1604]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="8.0">8</number>
weakly sclerotized, apophyses posteriores slightly longer and thicker than apophyses posteriores. Ostium surrounded by longitudinal sclerotized plates. Antrum long and wide, with strong spines in posterior part; colliculum indistinct. Ductus bursae wide, with band of very small internal spines extending also in corpus bursae; signum elongate, sickle-shaped, with transverse, weakly sclerotized plate covered by tiny spines (
<figureCitation box="[720,808,1733,1759]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 43" captionStartId="17.[151,270,1957,1981]" captionTargetBox="[172,1436,482,1910]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,465,1933]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 43. Perittia falciferella sp. n., female genitalia, holotype. 41, general view. Scale bar 0.2 mm; 42, caudal part of ductus bursae; 43, signum. Gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 477, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5178." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189260/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[775,808,1733,1759]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="43.0">43</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" box="[197,1348,1771,1798]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,289,1771,1797]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Biology</emphasis>
. The mined leaves of an unidentified, low growing monocot were collected in late March.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" box="[197,665,1810,1837]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,360,1810,1836]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Flight period</emphasis>
. April and probably May.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,354,1848,1874]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Distribution</emphasis>
. This species is presently known only from Kakamega Forest in the Western Province of 
<collectingCountry box="[151,228,1888,1914]" name="Kenya" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Kenya</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[243,326,1888,1914]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1176,1200]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,297,1155]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,297,1155]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Collecting localities in Kenya. 1, Arabuko Sokoke Forest National Park; 2, Aberdares National Park; 3, Hell’s Gate National Park; 4, Kakamega Forest National Reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189249/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Figs. 
<number box="[309,326,1888,1914]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="4.15">4</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[339,371,1888,1914]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="6.[151,259,1145,1169]" captionTargetBox="[409,1178,212,1101]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[390,1196,194,1121]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 15. Collecting localities of Elachistinae species in Kenya: 1, Arabuko Sokoke Forest National Park; 2, Aberdares National Park; 3, Hell's Gate National Park; 4, Kakamega Forest National Reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189252/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,843,1991]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,1926,1952]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[857,956,1927,1952]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">falcifera</emphasis>
(carrying a scythe or sickle) in reference to the shape of the signum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
